00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:46,000
But anyway, I couldn't not start.

90
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:52,000
So I decided to just start, and I started with how to use ChatGPT.

91
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:00,000
What I said during that ChatGPT usage session is so embarrassing now

92
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:08,000
When evaluating team members, export all Jira tickets and give them to ChatGPT 3.5

93
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:12,000
and have it summarize what this person did. That level.

94
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:20,000
And small tips like how to write formulas in Google Sheets. I started with those little things.

95
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:28,000
I shared things like that. And at that time, I was

96
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:34,000
deeply interested in developing RAG systems based on AI.

97
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Anyway, I was continuously learning about building agent systems, so I thought

98
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:48,000
I should teach some of this too, and I looked for people who could teach it.

99
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:58,000
I even contacted a YouTuber and got quotes, but I couldn't convince management

100
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,000
to go that far.

101
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:08,000
In the end, it was really good that case studies had much more power than knowing how-to.

102
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:16,000
Telling my story is good, and when colleagues around me are facing similar problems

103
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:24,000
and solving them, people gain confidence and think "I can do this too"

104
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,000
and take on challenges.

105
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:34,000
Seeing that, I was surprised too, and I felt that this was much more effective

106
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:40,000
than taking lectures.

107
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:48,000
That's right. So even though I initially planted a weak idea

108
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:56,000
some people tried first. As I saw these attempts succeed, from that point

109
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:04,000
other people started asking me questions, but not just "I asked ChatGPT and it didn't work"

110
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:12,000
They succeeded at the first step of "I think I can do something"

111
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
and failed at the second step.

112
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:26,000
So when I showed them methods and they solved it, it gave me much more sense of efficacy

113
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:28,000
I think.

114
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:38,000
After that, this happened. As cases kept being created and shared, at that time

115
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:46,000
what we were mainly doing was developing Chrome extensions or automating operations in Google Apps Script

116
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:52,000
with Google Sheets or Google Docs.

117
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,000
As you know, there's not that much you can do.

118
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,000
In that situation, people wanted to go further.

119
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:08,000
They wanted to automate the entire workflow, but when they asked ChatGPT, it said "Learn Python, learn TypeScript"

120
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,000
"Run Node.js" - people were getting guidance like that.

121
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:18,000
But these non-developers came to me asking "How do I do Python?"

122
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:20,000
"My head is going to explode."

123
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,000
"What should I do? Please teach me."

124
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:28,000
These kinds of inquiries started coming in, and I wondered, is it right to make these people do this?

125
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:30,000
What should I do?

126
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:36,000
Just saying "you can do it" didn't seem like enough. I thought about that a lot.

127
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:44,000
So I thought, let's connect them with developers, and that's how

128
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,000
Myrealtrip Kmong started.

129
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:54,000
Actually, with Myrealtrip Kmong at first, I approached this work thinking I needed to build a software system

130
00:12:54,000 --> 00:13:02,000
and I said I'd do it in a month, but then I wasted a month.

131
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:06,000
That's what happened.

132
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:10,000
I'll explain the lesson a bit more later.

133
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
But Myrealtrip Kmong launched 5 projects and then we just closed it.

134
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:20,000
Actually, even running Myrealtrip Kmong was really difficult.

135
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:28,000
Because we had to connect business experts with development experts, but developers don't understand the business

136
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:36,000
so they obviously can't solve their problems. To raise their understanding to that level required a lot of interviews and analysis.

137
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:44,000
And this was basically a bidding competition program, so when 2 or more people applied, we had to select one

138
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,000
That's how the program was structured.

139
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:52,000
So an unspecified number of people had to understand the business.

140
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:00,000
So I spent almost a week just interviewing and taking screenshots.

141
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:08,000
That was difficult, but the real problem was after all the software was delivered.

142
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Maintenance was the issue.

143
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:18,000
These people paid a service fee and received delivered software.

144
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:24,000
In that state, when maintenance issues arose, they couldn't solve them.

145
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:28,000
They don't know Python, so how can they fix a Python program they received?

146
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,000
That situation happened.

147
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:38,000
And quite emptily, the developers kept solving those maintenance issues.

148
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
But they had no motivation at all.

149
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:46,000
They briefly worked on things that didn't align with their goals at all.

150
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:50,000
Actually, the reason they could do it was the prize money.

151
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:58,000
It was all about the prize money, and once the one-time prize was paid, the problem solvers

152
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:02,000
didn't really need to maintain it actively.

153
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
That's how it was.

154
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:12,000
And as I said, since it wasn't their business or goal, no matter how hard they worked on it

155
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:14,000
it wouldn't reflect in their performance.

156
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:18,000
So I felt again at that time.

157
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:20,000
People must solve their own problems.

158
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:28,000
But thankfully at that time

159
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:30,000
we have a finance and accounting team.

160
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:40,000
The team leader, who had never done software development or engineering

161
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:48,000
built a Qt-based desktop standalone application in Python to automate their work

162
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:54,000
automating Excel manual work.

