00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Beyond doing it themselves, they assigned team members "do this, do that" and made them present weekly.

164
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
I didn't know, actually.

165
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:06,000
That person is now a member of our team.

166
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,000
Seeing that gave me courage too.

167
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:16,000
With Cursor's features improving, it became possible.

168
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,000
The world was changing so much.

169
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:24,000
So from then on, non-developers can do everything.

170
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:32,000
They can make web services, Chrome extensions, standalone applications - they can make everything

171
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:36,000
I gained that confidence then and closed Myrealtrip Kmong.

172
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:44,000
So the program we started again

173
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:46,000
is the AI Champion Training Program.

174
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:52,000
As we wrote, the core principle is solving your own problems.

175
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:56,000
And this program was initially run very ad-hoc.

176
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:00,000
People would say "I want to do this" and come join, things like that.

177
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:08,000
As we gradually established a framework, I thought about what program we could benchmark

178
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:12,000
and thought Y Combinator's batch program was somewhat similar.

179
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:18,000
Except for investment, their mentoring program seems similar to ours.

180
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,000
We run it in batches.

181
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:28,000
So how we work now is - I couldn't really put photos here but

182
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:36,000
we open office hours for 2 hours a day, and people working on projects can come anytime within those 2 hours.

183
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:44,000
Our team member acts as a tutor and is present, and we sync up with each person who comes about their current situation

184
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:52,000
what problems they're facing, and we just try to solve it together for about 30 minutes.

185
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:00,000
If they gain knowledge or if I can prove that something is possible, they take it back

186
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
and try it themselves.

187
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:10,000
We're doing a lot of these things, and among the completed projects

188
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:18,000
let me introduce a few. A designer made a Figma plugin to create advertising materials

189
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:26,000
It was originally an animation but you can't see it now, but when you run the plugin

190
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:28,000
a modal window pops up like that.

191
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:36,000
If you input some parameters there, since we're a travel company, for travel promotion materials

192
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:44,000
it renders each card that goes on the promotion page. So when you input a product ID

193
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:50,000
it extracts the properties, how should I put it.

194
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:52,000
For example, if it's a hotel.

195
00:18:52,000 --> 00:19:00,000
It randomly picks a few hotel room photos or pool photos and fills them as card content, and for the hotel's

196
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:08,000
detailed information text, it sends a call to the Anthropic API and

197
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:16,000
generates hooking phrases, and fills different card types - horizontal, vertical, square

198
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:22,000
with these templates to generate them instantly. That's the plugin they made.

199
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:26,000
The second one is also advertising.

200
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:38,000
They made a back office web application for their business like that, and

201
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:46,000
made the company's official homepage, and a marketer made an airline price comparison site

202
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:54,000
to increase traffic to our flights - they did experiments like that too.

203
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:58,000
The lessons learned here are about four.

204
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:06,000
First, in our case-sharing sessions, seeing colleagues next to you succeed and gaining confidence is most important.

205
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Rather than what power tools you can use or how to use them, just having confidence that you can do it is much more

206
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:16,000
important.

207
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:22,000
Second, it's best when someone with ownership does this work.

208
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:30,000
In Myrealtrip Kmong, when someone without ownership solved problems, communication costs were very high and it wasn't

209
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:32,000
easy to sustain.

210
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:40,000
Third, we always run with a small team. I started as a team of one, and now

211
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:44,000
we're 3 people. For a while it was 2 people.

212
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:52,000
So we're also making a lot of efforts to work AI-natively, and as you can see here, when champions

213
00:20:52,000 --> 00:21:00,000
apply for a batch, we created pre-interviews to get more

214
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:04,000
specific answers we want.

215
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:10,000
And finally, start quickly and visualize.

216
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:18,000
This is two things. Actually, for the Myrealtrip Kmong project, I wasted a month trying to build a system, but after meeting with my leader

217
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:22,000
we made the first case in 15 minutes and launched immediately.

218
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:24,000
Ignoring all the system.

219
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:32,000
Actually, I witnessed my developer clumsiness again

220
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
at that moment.

221
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And second, this is about raising literacy, how can we effectively

222
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
gain motivation and do this?

223
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:50,000
What you see here isn't about using coding tools.

224
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:54,000
